## Getting started with Arm Mbed OS

### Introduction

The purpose of this workshop is to help users get acquainted with the Arm Mbed OS ecosystem and tools. The entry point for Mbed OS is [ http://os.mbed.com](http://os.mbed.com). There, you find boards, modules, component libraries, an online compiler and offline tools to complement. The Arm Mbed tools work on all operating systems (Linux, Mac and Windows) and always work with at least ARMCC, IARCC and GCC. The Mbed tools are free for developers, and the software is available under the commercially friendly Apache 2.0 license.
Whether you want to develop online and collaborate with the community, offline behind a corporate firewall, use GitHub or private Git or Mercurial servers, the Arm Mbed ecosystem is here to help you as a platform to enable your projects. We are here to serve as a platform to make it easier for you to build your product.
Please note that there is also a [YouTube playlist](http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLiVCejcvpsetJ1n9nRXzLWvE4dp4RwGOf) for getting started with Mbed. This document is best viewed as a digital document. Here is a permalink to the document in case you are viewing it offline.

### os.mbed.com overview

Right now we are only talking about Mbed OS ( [os.mbed.com](http://os.mbed.com)), which makes up the embedded side of the Mbed ecosystem. We discuss the other half, Arm Mbed Cloud ( [cloud.mbed.com](http://cloud.mbed.com)), in a different document. The two products have separate websites on the mbed.com domain, and you can switch websites at the top of the webpage.

![](//TODO: Replace with image)

The Mbed OS ecosystem includes:

- Mbed [Online Compiler](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/tools/arm-mbed-online-compiler.html) - an online code environment.
- Arm [Mbed CLI](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/tools/installation-and-setup.html)- offline command-line interface for all things Mbed: compile, test and automate.
- [Hardware](https://os.mbed.com/hardware/) - Partner [boards](http://developer.mbed.org/platforms) and [modules](https://os.mbed.com/modules/) are certified &#39;Mbed Enabled&#39; to &#39;just work&#39;.
- [Components](https://os.mbed.com/components/) - a database of drivers and example code for common peripherals.
- [API Reference](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/reference/index.html) - official APIs and examples.
- [Tutorials](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/tutorials/index.html) - in-depth walkthroughs of a specific topic.
- [Forums](http://os.mbed.com/forum/) and [Questions](http://os.mbed.com/questions/) - great assets for community knowledge and growth.

#### Hardware

There are 3 pages of hardware. Boards are complete development kits that make it easy to prototype both a target MCU and a DAPLink interface circuit for programming and debugging the target MCU. Modules are made for going to production and are target MCUs with connectivity that has been certified for reuse. Having a module makes it easy to go to production and get your idea to market. Finally, there is the components page, which has drivers and example code for common components. The community members contribute the drivers they create because that makes it easier for everyone. Why rewrite a driver when you can reuse someone else&#39;s?

The [Boards](http://developer.mbed.org/platforms) and [Modules](https://os.mbed.com/modules/) pages contain a list of every target MCU officially supported in the Mbed ecosystem. There are links on each board and module page to add the board or module as a target to your compiler, to buy the board or module, pinout diagrams, firmware updates and bug fixes. It is important that you look at the platform page for the board you are using to find what the pin names are called and check for firmware updates.

#### Components database

The [components database](http://os.mbed.com/components) consists of libraries with examples and schematics for a wide variety of hardware components. The goal of this section is to eliminate the frustration of using a new part by leveraging prewritten drivers and sample applications for a given component. For example, if you want an RFID transceiver, search the components database for &quot;RFID&quot;, and choose the appropriate transceiver. Then you have the option of importing sample code into your compiler to take the component for a test drive.

![](//TODO: Replace with image)

#### Documentation

The [documentation](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest) section is exactly what it sounds like. For the full Mbed OS APIs with example implementations, look at the [Reference](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/reference/index.html) section. For a more in-depth walkthrough, look at the t [utorials](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/tutorials/index.html).

#### Forums and questions

The [forum](http://developer.mbed.org/forum/) is an excellent place to ask questions about anything and get a quick response from the community. Mostly community members moderate it, and it is a source for tips, tricks and advice for the Arm Mbed platforms. 

![](data:image/*;base64,)

#### Code examples

You can find code examples for existing components in the components database or by using the search function. The [mbed\_examples team](http://developer.mbed.org/teams/mbed_example) page has great sample projects demonstrating the Arm Mbed API.

### The Mbed Online Compiler

The Mbed Online Compiler enables you to either write your code from scratch or import an existing project and modify it to suit your needs. The compiler allows for customization of platform target, drivers, multiple projects and more.

#### Multilanguage support

The Mbed Online Compiler supports multiple languages and color schemes. In the bottom right of the Mbed Online Compiler, you can select your language and color scheme.

![](//TODO: Replace with image)

#### Import code to the Mbed Online Compiler

There are two methods of importing the code into the Mbed Online Compiler: using the site&#39;s search bar and using the compiler&#39;s Import button.

##### The search bar method

The search bar method starts at the top of the page on developer.mbed.org. Input the keywords to whatever project you are interested in finding:

For example, if you only want code examples, you can just search for code. If you want to see if a component is in the components database, you can search just the components database.

Once you are ready to test your project, click **Compile** at the top of the page.

If you project does not have any issues it will compile successfully. This will be noted by a **green** arrow and the word &quot;Success!&quot; in the Console Output area at the bottom of the compiler screen. On a successful compile, the browser automatically downloads the program to your Downloads folder.

If there is a problem with the code, then the program output describes the issue. To view where the problem is, double click on the error description, and the code editing tab jumps to and highlights the offending line of code.

#### Drag and drop to the Mbed board to program it

Once you have compiled your code and downloaded it to your computer, programming the Mbed board is a drag and drop.

1. Find the file generated by the compiler. By default, it is in your Downloaded folder.
2. Drag the file to the Mbed board.
	![](//TODO: Replace with image)

1. Allow a couple of seconds for the Mbed board to transfer the file. A copy dialog appears, and some lights flash on the board. (On \*nix systems, you can also use the &#39;cp&#39; command for the same effect).
2. Restart the board to initiate the code.

#### Success vs. failure: ambulance lights

Sometimes code fails to run. This can either be an issue with the code being written incorrectly or being compiled for the wrong board.

If the code fails at the hardware level, &quot;ambulance lights&quot; flash on the board. This notifies you that something has gone terribly wrong. The most common reason is uploading code meant for one board onto another. You can remedy this by recompiling the code for the correct platform and reloading it onto the board.

### Arm Mbed CLI

For offline development, we have the Mbed command-line interface. The Mbed CLI is the backend for the Mbed Online Compiler wrapped up into a command-line tool. Although not necessary, the CLI makes a few more advanced operations easier.

#### Installation

Mbed CLI works with Windows, Mac and Linux. You can find the most up-to-date installation instructions : [https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/tools/installation-and-setup.html](https://os.mbed.com/docs/latest/tools/installation-and-setup.html). There is an installer for Windows, but for OSX and Linux, you need to install Python 2.7.12+ and then install Mbed CLI from pip using the command &#39;pip install mbed-cli&#39;. You now need to install GCC.

#### Setup

For Mbed CLI&#39;s full functionality, please see the Mbed CLI details: [https://os.mbed.com/docs/v5.8/tools/working-with-mbed-cli.html](https://os.mbed.com/docs/v5.8/tools/working-with-mbed-cli.html).

Run the following commands with your board plugged in:

`mbed detect`- tells you what board is plugged into your machine.

`mbed config --global target auto` - detect what board is plugged into your computer and compiles for it.

`mbed config --global toolchain GCC\_ARM` - all projects compile with GCC.

`mbed config -L` - checks your configuration.

#### Use

`mbed import &lt;URL&gt;` - clone an Mbed repository to your machine. For example `mbed import [www.github.com/ArmMbed/mbed-os-example-blinky.git](http://www.github.com/ArmMbed/mbed-os-example-blinky.git)` imports the blinky program to your computer.

To compile your program, run `cd mbed-os-example-blinky` ,and then run the compile command `mbed compile`. This compiles your program using GCC for the target plugged into your computer. To set the target or compiler explicitly, run `mbed compile --target &lt;NAME&gt; --toolchain &lt;NAME`, where the target is the name of the board you get by running `mbed detect`.

**Tip:** Automatically flash your board by running `mbed compile --flash`.

There are more features in Mbed CLI, such as automated testing, compiler macro overrides and so much more. For those, we recommend reading the docs!



### Debugging

To debug your projects you can either use printf statements in your code and then view the output using a serial terminal: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jAMTXK9HjfU](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jAMTXK9HjfU) or you can export your program to a supported IDE. By default, Mbed supports Keil, IAR and GCC.

#### Exporting to IDE

##### Mbed Online Compiler

If you are using the Mbed Online Compiler, right click on your project, and select export.

![](//TODO: Replace with image)

Next, select your toolchain, and click export. A project file downloads to your machine.

![](//TODO: Replace with image)

##### Arm Mbed CLI - Offline

To export your project offline, type the command `mbed export --supported` to get a full list of your toolchain and target combinations. Then, run the command with the pair you select as follows `mbed export --ide &lt;IDE&gt; --target &lt;TARGET&gt;` . For example, to export to Uvision for a Nordic NRF52DK, use the command :

`mbed export --ide UVISION5 --target NRF52DK`

This video goes through all this: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PI1Kq9RSN\_Y](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PI1Kq9RSN_Y)



### Board firmware updates

If you have a problem with an out-of-the-box board, old firmware is a common culprit. To update the firmware for your board, go to the [platform page](http://developer.mbed.org/platforms/), select your board, and follow the instructions there.

**Tip** : If you are experiencing trouble connecting to your Mbed board, be sure to update both the target firmware and the interface chip firmware.

### Collaboration

The Mbed Online Compiler and Mbed CLI both support Git and Mercurial repositories. We recommend collaborating with the community by using the standard methodologies for those systems.

For Git, here is a great resource on how to submit a PR from forking, to committing to merging : [https://git-scm.com/doc](https://git-scm.com/doc). One of the better Git platforms out there is GitHub, which makes using Git even easier: [https://guides.github.com/activities/hello-world/](https://guides.github.com/activities/hello-world/)

For Mercurial, here is a great guide: [https://www.mercurial-scm.org/guide](https://www.mercurial-scm.org/guide)

In the Mbed Online Compiler you can also commit and publish your code either to the Mbed website or directly back to GitHub.
